      "abstract": "Abstract The public sphere is a pivotal concept in democratic theory. Conventionally, it is framed in a local/national context. In the classic Habermasian formulation, the public sphere is predicated on national media, a sovereign state, and participatory citizenry. However, under conditions of globalisation, the nation-state paradigm is subject to increasingly significant challenges. The advent of the network society is also destabilising the institutional foundations of the national public. These developments necessitate a reassessment of the public sphere as a territorially delimited realm. A reconstruction of Habermasian theory reveals how global interconnections may be providing the structural preconditions for the emergence of transnational public spheres. The categories of flows are threefold: communicative networks, governance networks, and activist networks. In certain issue-areas, all three preconditions may coalesce to produce an environment suitable for the emergence of transnational public spheres. However, the potential for the realisation of 'borderless' public spheres is circumscribed by key factors. Global communication is systematically distorted, global governance is democratically deficient, and the norms of critical publicity are difficult to sustain amongst highly differentiated virtual audiences. Unless these issues are addressed, the early promise of transnational networks as an emancipatory force will be neutralised. La esfera p\u00fablica es un concepto esencial en la teor\u00eda democr\u00e1tica. Convencionalmente, se ha conceptualizado tanto en un contexto local como nacional. En la cl\u00e1sica formulaci\u00f3n habermasiana, la esfera p\u00fablica se predica a trav\u00e9s de los medios nacionales, un estado soberano y una ciudadan\u00eda participante. Sin embargo, bajo las condiciones de la globalizaci\u00f3n, el paradigma de naci\u00f3n-estado est\u00e1 sometido a retos significativos que van en aumento. La entrada de la sociedad en red est\u00e1 desestabilizando tambi\u00e9n las bases institucionales del p\u00fablico nacional. Estos desarrollos necesitan un replanteamiento de la esfera p\u00fablica como un dominio territorialmente delimitado. Una reconstrucci\u00f3n de la teor\u00eda habermasiana revela c\u00f3mo las interconexiones globales pueden proveer las precondiciones estructurales para el surgimiento de esferas p\u00fablicas transnacionales. Las categor\u00edas de las corrientes se dividen en tres: redes comunicativas, redes gubernamentales y redes de activistas. En ciertas \u00e1reas con problemas, todas las tres precondiciones tienen que fundirse para producir un ambiente adecuado para el establecimiento de las esferas p\u00fablicas transnacionales. Sin embargo, el potencial para la realizaci\u00f3n de las esferas p\u00fablicas 'sin fronteras' se circunscribe por factores claves. La comunicaci\u00f3n global es distorsionada sistem\u00e1ticamente, la autoridad global es democr\u00e1ticamente deficiente y las normas de la publicidad cr\u00edtica son dif\u00edciles de sostener entre audiencias virtuales altamente diferenciadas. A menos que se resuelvan estos problemas, la promesa inicial de las redes globales como una fuerza liberalizadora, ser\u00e1 neutralizada. Acknowledgements I am indebted to the guidance and advice of Professor Anthony McGrew throughout my postgraduate studies, during which this article was conceived. An earlier draft of this paper was presented at a Research Seminar at the University of Huddersfield, and I thank the attendees for their feedback. I am also grateful for constructive comments on a previous draft by Professor Barrie Axford and the anonymous reviewers. Notes 1 Of course, Habermas's substantial oeuvre cannot be easily summarized, but there have been interesting linkages with the themes of STPS in his later work. For example, he has conceded the salience of contemporaneous counter publics during the bourgeois era (1992b), and considered the ambiguous implications of new media for discursive democracy (1998). He has argued for new democratic steering mechanisms to be developed in the nascent 'postnational constellation' and shown particular interest in the potential of the European Union to develop constitutional solidarities (2000). He has also continued to assert that presently 'the necessary infrastructure for a wide-ranging generation of diverse public opinions exists only within the confines of nation states' (Habermas, 2001 Habermas, J. 2001. Why Europe needs a constitution. New Left Review, : 5\u201326. [Google Scholar], p. 18). 2 Fraser (2005) Fraser, N. 2005. Transnationalizing the Public Sphere, http://www.republicart.net/disc/publicum/fraser01_en.htm [Google Scholar] also claims that classical public sphere theory presupposes the existence of a Westphalian national economy subject to state regulation, a national language, and a national literary culture. 3 It is also important to note that transnational deliberative spaces were manifest during the eighteenth century, indicating that networking forms of social organisation have historical precursors. See Aravamudan's (1999) Aravamudan, S. 1999. Tropicopolitans: Colonialism and Agency, 1688-1804, Durham, NC: Duke University Press. [Crossref] , [Google Scholar] analysis of colonial-era literature, Gilroy's (1993) Gilroy, P. 1993. The Black Atlantic: Modernity and Double Consciousness, Cambridge, MA: Harvard University Press. [Google Scholar] discussion of black vernacular cultures, and Rediker and Linebaugh's (2000) Linebaugh, P. and Rediker, M. 2000. The Many-Headed Hydra: Sailors, Slaves, Commoners, and the Hidden History of the Revolutionary Atlantic, Boston, MA: Beacon Press. [Google Scholar] study on the multi-ethnic Atlantic working class. It is my contention that new potentialities for emergent transnational public spheres arise when network structures become the prevailing modalities of organisation in contemporary society. As will be seen, the unique qualities of ICT such as the Internet are instrumental in invoking these prospects. 4 Mitzen (2005) Mitzen, J. 2005. Reading Habermas in anarchy: multilateral diplomacy and global public spheres. American Political Science Review, 99(3): 401\u2013417. [Crossref], [Web of Science \u00ae] , [Google Scholar] and Lynch (1999) Lynch, M. 1999. State Interests and Public Spheres: The International Politics of Jordan's Identity, New York: Columbia University Press. [Google Scholar] have applied a public sphere perspective to inter-state relations. Although they offer interesting insights, I argue that the radical potential of public sphere theory is curtailed when it neglects non-state actors, particularly those at the margins of society. Historically, subaltern counter publics have been fertile sites of political activism and emancipatory transformation. 5 The extent of this transformation is matter of controversy, ranging from assertions of the continuing primacy of the state to claims of its demise (Held & McGrew, 2003 Held, D. and McGrew, A. 2003. The Global Transformations Reader, Edited by: Held, D. and McGrew, A. Cambridge: Polity. [Google Scholar]). 6 See Dahlberg (2001) Dahlberg, L. 2001. Extending the public sphere through cyberspace: the case of Minnesota E-democracy. First Monday, 6(3) http://www.firstmonday.dk/issues/issue6_3/dahlberg/index.html[Crossref] , [Google Scholar] for an intriguing analysis of the Minnesota E-Democracy project, a largely successful attempt at structuring online political discourse along public sphere principles.",
